WEBVTT

00:02.654 --> 00:04.656
[laughs]

00:06.310 --> 00:08.008
♪

00:10.358 --> 00:11.750
[shrieks]

00:17.147 --> 00:18.931
[school bell rings]

00:21.108 --> 00:22.326
[burps]

00:22.370 --> 00:25.199
[tires screech]

00:25.242 --> 00:27.244
D'oh!

00:27.288 --> 00:29.072
[grunts]

00:29.116 --> 00:31.118
[1960s-style sitcom theme
playing]

00:36.166 --> 00:39.126
HOMER:
My Three Kids.

00:48.352 --> 00:50.615
WILLIE:
Everyone, out of my kitchen!

00:52.835 --> 00:56.143
Brandine, do I come off
as a yokel or a hayseed?

00:56.186 --> 00:58.101
Well, you are versatile,
darlin'.

00:58.145 --> 01:00.930
You can play anyone
in the trailer trash spectrum.

01:00.973 --> 01:04.238
A-yeah, I'm a regular
Benedict Cabbage-Patch.

01:04.281 --> 01:05.456
[chuckles]

01:05.500 --> 01:07.763
RALPH:
Meow!

01:07.806 --> 01:09.808
Community thespians,

01:09.852 --> 01:13.290
today we returnto turn-of-the-century Oklahoma.

01:13.334 --> 01:15.945
Farm boys are farming.
Cowboys are cowing.

01:15.988 --> 01:18.556
And, Carl, do you think
your character Ike Skidmore

01:18.600 --> 01:22.125
is bringing his cell phone
to the box social in 1906?

01:22.169 --> 01:24.127
I see him
as a forward-thinking guy,

01:24.171 --> 01:25.911
a tech first adopter.

01:25.955 --> 01:29.045
You know how I see him?
Not played by you!

01:29.089 --> 01:31.352
Lenny, get yourself
out of that horse's patoot.

01:31.395 --> 01:32.918
You're Ike Skidmore.

01:32.962 --> 01:35.399
Yee-haw! A speaking part!

01:35.443 --> 01:37.401
This is gonna be tan-fastic.

01:37.445 --> 01:40.578
Geez, don't make it
into a song and dance.

01:40.622 --> 01:43.581
♪ I've got spurs that
jingle, jangle, jing... ♪

01:43.625 --> 01:45.017
[exclaims]

01:45.061 --> 01:47.281
My spur's stuck in my eye!

01:47.324 --> 01:48.978
Carl, you're back in.

01:49.021 --> 01:50.327
Well, only with
Lenny's blessing.

01:50.371 --> 01:53.156
-You don't have it.
-I'm doing it anyway.

01:53.200 --> 01:56.420
Okay, Marge, this is
your big song number.

01:56.464 --> 01:59.771
You're Ado Annie,
the girl who cain't say no.

01:59.815 --> 02:02.774
Now, do you have any qualms
about playing this part?

02:02.818 --> 02:06.256
-No.
-Wrong, wrong!
You cain't say no.

02:06.300 --> 02:07.866
Now, where's my handsome Curly?

02:07.910 --> 02:09.433
Right here.

02:09.477 --> 02:12.393
Now, this I can work with.

02:12.436 --> 02:13.350
HOMER:
Okay, Maggie,

02:13.394 --> 02:15.439
what shall we do
while Mommy rehearses?

02:15.483 --> 02:16.962
The dog track is closed.

02:17.006 --> 02:18.355
You can come visit me!

02:18.399 --> 02:19.965
I didn't hear that.

02:20.009 --> 02:22.185
Hmm, what shall we do?

02:23.491 --> 02:25.188
Why is this place so popular?

02:25.232 --> 02:28.017
Do they serve booze?
Is it a baby fight club?

02:28.060 --> 02:29.888
Is there a big-screen TV?

02:29.932 --> 02:32.108
Do they serve booze?
Are there free doughnuts?

02:32.152 --> 02:33.414
Meet Batman?

02:33.457 --> 02:34.893
[gasps]
Do they serve booze?

02:34.937 --> 02:36.982
[baby talk]:
We're going to find out.

02:37.026 --> 02:39.985
Why in the hell
is Daddy and Me class packed?

02:40.029 --> 02:43.902
You'll understand everything
when Chloe comes out.

02:43.946 --> 02:45.687
Quiet, quiet, she's coming.

02:45.730 --> 02:47.558
I borrowed my granddaughter
just for this.

02:47.602 --> 02:49.647
I said I was taking her
to feed the ducks.

02:49.691 --> 02:51.649
[scoffs]
Like I have bread money.

02:51.693 --> 02:52.824
-Hi, dads.
-[dads greet]

02:52.868 --> 02:55.566
Who's ready to do
the wiggle worm dance?

02:55.610 --> 02:58.003
I vant to viggle
like the vorm, ja.

02:58.047 --> 03:00.049
♪ A wiggle worm giggles ♪

03:00.092 --> 03:01.877
♪ And a wiggle worm waggles ♪

03:01.920 --> 03:05.489
♪ Let's all wiggle
like the wiggle worm does. ♪

03:05.533 --> 03:09.363
Oh, I get it, she's sexy.

03:09.406 --> 03:10.929
[growls]

03:10.973 --> 03:12.627
Maggie! How long
have you been here?

03:12.670 --> 03:15.412
♪

03:15.456 --> 03:18.459
Why does this line say "Curt"
when I'm talking to Curly?

03:18.502 --> 03:21.375
No, you see, "curt"
is in parentheses.

03:21.418 --> 03:23.681
It tells you
how to say the line.

03:23.725 --> 03:26.118
Obviously lying--
yeah, no, I knew that.

03:26.162 --> 03:29.383
Impressed noise.
You really know your stuff.

03:29.426 --> 03:30.601
Okay, actors,

03:30.645 --> 03:32.473
in the words
of William Shakespeare,

03:32.516 --> 03:34.475
find your "X" and shut up.

03:34.518 --> 03:36.477
Geez, all right, easy.

03:36.520 --> 03:39.958
All I ask is that
you give me the performance

03:40.002 --> 03:43.832
I have pictured in my head but
have not communicated to you.

03:43.875 --> 03:47.139
Our curtain opens
on sun-drenched fields

03:47.183 --> 03:50.186
of undulating golden corn.

03:50.230 --> 03:52.493
♪ O... ♪

03:52.536 --> 03:55.147
Stop, stop, stop!

03:55.191 --> 03:56.932
This set is terrible.

03:56.975 --> 04:00.109
That corn isn't as high
as an elephant's eye.

04:00.152 --> 04:02.720
Oh, you wanted the corn
to be high.

04:02.764 --> 04:05.506
I have never seen
such incompetence and idiocy

04:05.549 --> 04:06.724
in a theater.

04:06.768 --> 04:09.379
You have made me hate you all.

04:09.423 --> 04:12.382
Excuse my salty language
in front of Aunt Eller,

04:12.426 --> 04:13.949
but why don't you
just take a hike?

04:13.992 --> 04:15.951
[gasps]
Oh.

04:15.994 --> 04:17.561
Get lost.

04:20.216 --> 04:22.305
Losing temper,
we don't want you here.

04:22.349 --> 04:26.135
Turns to cast, I saved the play.

04:26.178 --> 04:28.529
Marge, surely you
want me to stay.

04:28.572 --> 04:30.400
Actually, no.

04:30.444 --> 04:34.796
For the last time, that's
the one word you cain't say.

04:34.839 --> 04:37.102
This is mine.
I brought it from home.

04:37.146 --> 04:38.452
Now what do we do?

04:38.495 --> 04:41.324
I learned-a to speak
like-a the Oklahoma for this?

04:41.368 --> 04:43.718
Con-a sarn it.

04:43.761 --> 04:46.242
[grunting]

04:46.286 --> 04:49.158
Everyone, stop, just stop.

04:49.201 --> 04:50.594
Chief, no more gunplay.

04:50.638 --> 04:52.596
But I wanna.

04:52.640 --> 04:54.685
[indistinct yelling]

04:54.729 --> 04:57.601
Just listen to me!

04:57.645 --> 05:00.169
What if I directed the play?

05:00.212 --> 05:03.477
Hey, that's a good idea. I mean,she directs Homer and the kids

05:03.520 --> 05:05.000
out of the house every morning.

05:05.043 --> 05:06.741
And I direct traffic.

05:06.784 --> 05:08.395
That's a stupid analogy.

05:08.438 --> 05:11.136
I think Marge makes us all
feel good about ourselves.

05:11.180 --> 05:13.443
[sighs]:
Mmm.

05:13.487 --> 05:15.402
Yelling in unison.

05:15.445 --> 05:18.709
ALL:
Marge! Marge! Marge! Yay!

05:18.753 --> 05:22.147
Wait a minute, if thisis a real gun, where's the prop?

05:22.191 --> 05:24.367
[gasps]
Poor Lou.

05:24.411 --> 05:26.151
All right, you asked for it.

05:26.195 --> 05:29.372
Uh, wh-wh-who wants
Oklahoma!tickets? Front row.

05:29.416 --> 05:30.591
I can get you three together.

05:37.641 --> 05:40.470
[groans] This is
a really complicated show.

05:40.514 --> 05:41.602
So much gingham.

05:41.645 --> 05:44.213
We need a show
that we can actually pull off

05:44.256 --> 05:45.475
in Springfield.

05:45.519 --> 05:48.609
Small cast, simple sets,
and some hip-hop,

05:48.652 --> 05:50.437
but not real hip-hop.

05:50.480 --> 05:52.613
Great, but I got
to be someplace,

05:52.656 --> 05:54.571
so, real quick,
the best kind of original show

05:54.615 --> 05:57.269
is one that rips off a big hit.What's the biggest hit?

05:57.313 --> 05:58.619
Hellzapoppin'!

05:58.662 --> 06:01.404
No, Hamilton
by Lin-Manuel Miranda.

06:01.448 --> 06:03.101
Oh, the guy from In the Heights.

06:03.145 --> 06:05.756
Now, how did I know that?
I'm back!

06:05.800 --> 06:08.890
All right, who's our
Alexander Hamilton?

06:08.933 --> 06:12.328
That would be me.
Thanks to this furnace filter,

06:12.372 --> 06:15.679
you won't be saying
"burr" anymore.

06:15.723 --> 06:20.205
No, our most famous
historical figure...

06:20.249 --> 06:22.425
[gasps]
Jebediah Springfield!

06:22.469 --> 06:25.559
I'll write a musical biography,warts and all.

06:25.602 --> 06:27.474
I can't see how that could fail.

06:27.517 --> 06:30.433
Now I'm in a hurry-- Maggieand I have a Daddy and Me class.

06:30.477 --> 06:32.043
Aren't you forgetting something?

06:32.087 --> 06:34.524
Keys, wallet, I don't think so.

06:34.568 --> 06:37.005
[chuckling]: Oh, sure.
I'm happy to take Maggie.

06:37.048 --> 06:38.572
You sure like that class.

06:38.615 --> 06:42.576
Oh, uh, some dads just love
to be with their little girls.

06:42.619 --> 06:44.621
-Can I go?
-Sorry, no.

06:44.665 --> 06:47.276
"Humpty Dumpty sat on a wall.

06:47.319 --> 06:48.799
Humpty Dumpty had a great fall."

06:48.843 --> 06:50.279
Oh...

06:50.322 --> 06:53.891
Poor little eggy,
leaking your goo.

06:53.935 --> 06:58.287
The Red Queen's not looking,
I'll kiss your boo-boo.

06:58.330 --> 07:01.159
Humpty J. Dumpty,
are you eating yourself?

07:01.203 --> 07:03.379
Maybe.

07:06.643 --> 07:08.123
[Marge groans]

07:08.166 --> 07:10.778
Excuse me, excuse me, pal.
Take care of your kid.

07:12.562 --> 07:14.564
I-I'm so sorry. I was just...

07:14.608 --> 07:16.740
Yeah, I know what you were just.

07:16.784 --> 07:17.915
LISA:
Let's see...

07:17.959 --> 07:21.397
killed a bear, founded a town,
died of a beaver bite.

07:21.441 --> 07:22.703
Lis, you're gonna love it.

07:22.746 --> 07:23.878
I came up
with the perfect opening.

07:23.921 --> 07:25.488
Okay...

07:25.532 --> 07:28.665
[clears throat]
♪ Lisa is so stupid,
so very, very stupid ♪

07:28.709 --> 07:32.539
♪ So dumb and stupid
and smelly, too ♪

07:32.582 --> 07:35.672
♪ She has a real bad temper,
a bad, bad temper ♪

07:35.716 --> 07:38.501
♪ And she's smelly, too! ♪

07:38.545 --> 07:40.503
You're just motivating me.

07:40.547 --> 07:42.505
I need to finish this.

07:42.549 --> 07:44.072
[whimpers]

07:44.115 --> 07:46.553
Ah, my muse.

07:47.554 --> 07:48.511
MARGE:
Okay,

07:48.555 --> 07:50.861
my first day as director.
[sighs]

07:50.905 --> 07:53.124
So hard to dress for respect.

07:53.168 --> 07:57.128
No. No.

07:57.172 --> 07:59.130
No.

07:59.174 --> 08:00.915
Got it.

08:04.005 --> 08:05.789
[gasps]

08:07.748 --> 08:09.793
Hey-a, buddy, what'll it be?

08:09.837 --> 08:11.142
Moe, it's me.

08:11.186 --> 08:13.623
Midge! I thought it was
Hillary Clinton.

08:13.667 --> 08:15.190
Give me a vodka, straight up.

08:15.233 --> 08:17.235
Are you sure you're not Hillary?

08:18.802 --> 08:22.153
Our new production will be
Bloody Bloody Jebediah,

08:22.197 --> 08:24.939
a hip-hop musical
about our city's founder.

08:24.982 --> 08:26.680
Is it respectful?

08:26.723 --> 08:28.159
Not entirely.

08:28.203 --> 08:29.552
What?!

08:29.596 --> 08:31.772
Why don't we start
by going around the circle

08:31.815 --> 08:33.338
and saying what parts
we're playing.

08:33.382 --> 08:34.905
I'm Marge, the director.

08:34.949 --> 08:36.951
Luann, Jebediah's wife.

08:36.994 --> 08:41.172
Carl, Quarrelsome Settler. I gota bone to pick with this part.

08:41.216 --> 08:42.957
Beautiful, use it. Next.

08:43.000 --> 08:46.003
Lenny, Mayor of Shelbyville
and an ostrich.

08:50.007 --> 08:52.619
Frink, tech crew. Always crew.

08:52.662 --> 08:55.622
Hollywood only lets in
one Bill Nye in a generation.

08:55.665 --> 08:57.841
[exclaims]
With the nerdy and the hoyvik

08:57.885 --> 09:00.757
and the reference
only I understand.

09:00.801 --> 09:04.848
And, of course, our incredible
star, Sideshow Mel.

09:04.892 --> 09:06.763
Finally not a sidekick.

09:06.807 --> 09:09.287
This is my time to shine.

09:09.331 --> 09:11.725
Your first line is on page 37.

09:11.768 --> 09:12.769
What?!

09:12.813 --> 09:15.511
♪ Yo, Jebediah survived
the pox ♪

09:15.555 --> 09:16.860
♪ Never used clocks ♪

09:16.904 --> 09:18.993
♪ Didn't wear socks,
that's what we learned ♪

09:19.036 --> 09:22.257
♪ From examining his docs,
and now the mic drops. ♪

09:22.300 --> 09:23.693
Boom, et cetera.

09:23.737 --> 09:25.695
-[groans]
-Krusty, what's wrong?

09:25.739 --> 09:27.654
It's happened--
the worst possible thing

09:27.697 --> 09:29.830
that can happen to a performer.

09:29.873 --> 09:31.048
What do you mean?

09:31.092 --> 09:32.615
I'm in an article entitled,

09:32.659 --> 09:34.269
"Where Are They Now?"

09:34.312 --> 09:36.706
[sobs]

09:36.750 --> 09:39.230
Right above Judd Nelson
and New Coke.

09:39.274 --> 09:41.189
I'll tell you
where Judd Nelson is.

09:41.232 --> 09:44.018
He's on my show tonight.
[sobs]

09:46.760 --> 09:49.240
Ah. Fantastic!

09:49.284 --> 09:50.764
What's that thing
you were doing?

09:50.807 --> 09:54.419
Oh, uh, local theater.
You wouldn't be interested.

09:54.463 --> 09:56.770
Hey, I'm a performer, an artist,

09:56.813 --> 09:59.294
which means I'm always
interested in money.

09:59.337 --> 10:02.297
Live theater is the only thing
getting ratings these days.

10:02.340 --> 10:03.472
Who owns the rights?

10:03.515 --> 10:06.214
A Mrs. Marge Simpson.

10:06.257 --> 10:09.696
Oh, really?
Let's see what kind of bargain

10:09.739 --> 10:12.350
Mrs. Marge Simpson drives.

10:13.743 --> 10:15.832
So you'll get 80% of the profits

10:15.876 --> 10:18.705
while I get foreign distributionrights in Venezuela

10:18.748 --> 10:20.794
for a window of three weeks.

10:20.837 --> 10:23.144
[chuckles nervously, groans]

10:23.187 --> 10:26.451
So my little show's
gonna be on TV live?

10:26.495 --> 10:28.845
Yep. This is the first time
a woman has signed something

10:28.889 --> 10:31.500
with me where I didn't lose
custody of something.

10:31.543 --> 10:33.067
So where will we stage it?

10:33.110 --> 10:35.809
Outside,
where the lighting is free.

10:35.852 --> 10:37.898
Ooh, are you sure
that's not risky?

10:37.941 --> 10:41.031
Well, some would say I'm takinga risk with an original play

10:41.075 --> 10:45.296
and a first-time director, butshow business is based on risks.

10:45.340 --> 10:47.864
Risks and comic books.
Excuse me.

10:47.908 --> 10:49.866
[chuckles]

10:49.910 --> 10:53.914
So, Marge, are you ready
to beg me to come back?

10:53.957 --> 10:57.047
Actually, Llewellyn,
we're doing fine on our own.

10:57.091 --> 11:00.050
No need to grovel. You don't
actually have to say anything.

11:00.094 --> 11:01.530
Okay, fine, I'll come back.

11:01.573 --> 11:03.706
No one's asking you
to come back.

11:03.750 --> 11:06.100
You know what? Just for that,
I won't come back.

11:06.143 --> 11:09.886
-Fine.
-Please, I'm begging you,
take me back.

11:10.887 --> 11:13.063
All right, but beware,

11:13.107 --> 11:15.892
hell hath no fury
like a director scorned.

11:15.936 --> 11:17.502
Now, if you'll excuse me,

11:17.546 --> 11:20.114
I have to sneak my headshot
onto the wall.

11:20.157 --> 11:22.551
And poof.

11:22.594 --> 11:23.944
You're flushed, Plummer.

11:23.987 --> 11:26.424
I hired you to bus tables.

11:30.559 --> 11:33.910
-Hmm?
-I'm researching a role.

11:33.954 --> 11:35.956
[chomps]

11:39.350 --> 11:42.310
Now, Mom, before you go
into that production meeting,

11:42.353 --> 11:46.096
I want to pass along a quote
from F. Scott Fitzgerald.

11:46.140 --> 11:50.100
"Great art is the contemptof a great woman for small art."

11:50.144 --> 11:53.103
He actually said "man," but he'd
have wanted me to change it.

11:53.147 --> 11:55.540
Didn't he also say,
"Show me a hero

11:55.584 --> 11:57.978
and I'll write you a tragedy"?

11:58.021 --> 12:00.676
Yes, but he also said,

12:00.720 --> 12:03.853
"Never confuse a single defeat
with a final defeat."

12:03.897 --> 12:05.420
But didn't he also say,

12:05.463 --> 12:08.205
"There are no second acts
in American lives"?

12:08.249 --> 12:10.207
Just get in the meeting!

12:10.251 --> 12:12.470
The bagels are getting hard.

12:12.514 --> 12:13.994
[grunts happily]

12:14.037 --> 12:16.039
[doorbell rings]

12:16.997 --> 12:19.347
[chuckles]
There's my Jebediah.

12:19.390 --> 12:21.784
Marge, I'm leaving the show

12:21.828 --> 12:24.265
to fulfill a lifelong dream--

12:24.308 --> 12:26.920
playing Prospero in The Tempest.

12:26.963 --> 12:28.704
You can't quit now.

12:28.748 --> 12:30.271
We're live in three days.

12:30.314 --> 12:32.273
We have no understudy.

12:32.316 --> 12:36.059
And you were gonna bringthe edibles for the wrap party.

12:36.103 --> 12:38.061
Not my problem.

12:38.105 --> 12:40.977
There's nothing I enjoy more
than watching a director

12:41.021 --> 12:44.415
trying to talk an actor out
of leaving for a better part.

12:44.459 --> 12:46.809
[cackles]
Dramatic twist!

12:51.553 --> 12:53.860
♪ Sing a song of sixpence,
a pocketful of rye ♪

12:53.903 --> 12:57.472
♪ Four and 20 blackbirds
baked in a pie. ♪

12:57.515 --> 12:59.256
[cawing, chirping]

12:59.300 --> 13:01.868
Stay in there,
you stupid blackbirds!

13:01.911 --> 13:03.173
[screeching]

13:03.217 --> 13:05.175
Darling, you're supposed
to kill the blackbirds

13:05.219 --> 13:07.264
before you put them in the pie.

13:07.308 --> 13:09.527
Homie, Homie.

13:09.571 --> 13:10.964
[screeching]

13:11.007 --> 13:13.096
-Homie. Homie.
-Blackbirds! Blackbirds!

13:13.140 --> 13:14.619
Homie, wake up.

13:14.663 --> 13:16.099
What are you dreaming about?

13:16.143 --> 13:17.971
Uh, Daddy and Me class.

13:18.014 --> 13:20.103
You are a great father.

13:20.147 --> 13:23.063
Oh, I wish I felt
like a great director.

13:23.106 --> 13:25.674
Fine, if you want me to quit
the class, I'll do it.

13:25.717 --> 13:27.328
Who said anything
about quitting?

13:27.371 --> 13:30.287
I've had enough people
quit on me today.

13:30.331 --> 13:32.724
Marge, anyone who can raise
two girls and two boys

13:32.768 --> 13:34.465
the way you're doing
can do anything.

13:34.509 --> 13:36.511
You're gonna make it.

13:37.468 --> 13:39.514
I've got
a special announcement today.

13:39.557 --> 13:41.211
You're gonna wear the perfume
I bought you?

13:41.255 --> 13:42.517
Even better.

13:42.560 --> 13:44.084
Barry's divorce came through,

13:44.127 --> 13:47.130
so I'm able to leave this classand marry him.

13:47.174 --> 13:49.480
Come on up, Barry.

13:49.524 --> 13:51.004
[all groaning]

13:51.047 --> 13:52.657
Later, losers.

13:52.701 --> 13:55.138
Barry's not sitting
cross-legged anymore.

13:55.182 --> 13:56.574
Uh, why him?

13:56.618 --> 13:58.054
Maybe I have the cutest baby.

13:58.098 --> 14:00.448
Or maybe the first words
I got her to say were

14:00.491 --> 14:02.232
"I love you, Chloe."

14:02.276 --> 14:04.800
[gibbering]:
I love you, Chloe.

14:04.844 --> 14:07.455
We sang "Wheels on the Bus"
together.

14:07.498 --> 14:09.022
Well, that's it. Time to...

14:09.065 --> 14:11.589
[stammers]
Where's the baby I brought?

14:11.633 --> 14:15.506
Ah, geez. I won't be dating
her grandma anymore.

14:15.550 --> 14:17.465
[indistinct chatter]

14:17.508 --> 14:19.946
So I guess we're not
doing the class.

14:22.165 --> 14:26.126
Wait a minute, the part youliked was spending time with me?

14:26.169 --> 14:30.173
Aw. Well, I'll always dance
with you, sweetie.

14:30.217 --> 14:33.524
♪

14:34.569 --> 14:36.527
Hmm?
[gasping]

14:36.571 --> 14:37.877
[strains]

14:39.574 --> 14:41.968
Okay, no pressure,
but I need to find a new lead

14:42.011 --> 14:43.970
in the next 15 minutes.

14:44.013 --> 14:45.188
Preferably a name.

14:45.232 --> 14:46.973
Is Bumblebee Man available?

14:47.016 --> 14:49.410
No, he's playing Don Quixote
in Man of La Mancha.

14:49.453 --> 14:52.979
Damn it. Why is this town's
theater scene so vibrant?

14:53.022 --> 14:56.069
I'm here to audition
for the part of Macbeth.

14:56.112 --> 14:57.505
It's not Macbeth.

14:57.548 --> 14:59.072
-Is it Macduff?
-Not Macduff.

14:59.115 --> 15:01.988
Well, there's no other parts
worth playing!

15:02.031 --> 15:03.554
That's it. We're doomed.

15:03.598 --> 15:05.165
We'll just have a bake sale.

15:05.208 --> 15:06.862
Will you serve haggis?

15:06.906 --> 15:08.603
-No.
-I'm out.

15:08.646 --> 15:11.998
[deep voice]:
♪ A pioneer with no fear ♪

15:12.041 --> 15:14.000
♪ Shooting deer ♪

15:14.043 --> 15:16.002
♪ On the frontier... ♪

15:16.045 --> 15:17.829
Spotlight that singer.

15:17.873 --> 15:21.398
♪ And the crowds all cheer ♪

15:21.442 --> 15:24.445
♪ Jebediah Springfield ♪

15:24.488 --> 15:28.449
♪ Found the town right here. ♪

15:28.492 --> 15:29.972
[regular voice]:
Yes, glavin, it's me,

15:30.016 --> 15:35.325
with the Gomer Pyle voice and
the unexpectedly good singing.

15:35.369 --> 15:36.631
You've got the part.

15:36.674 --> 15:37.632
[deep voice]:
♪ Thank you. ♪

15:37.675 --> 15:39.068
Save your voice.

15:39.112 --> 15:42.071
[regular voice]:
All right, then.

15:42.115 --> 15:43.638
[thunder rolls]

15:43.681 --> 15:46.467
Marge, as your producer, I'm
gonna inform you of a problem,

15:46.510 --> 15:48.686
then blame you
if you can't solve it.

15:48.730 --> 15:50.688
[sighs]
Now what?

15:50.732 --> 15:53.430
There's one thing a first-time
director cannot control.

15:53.474 --> 15:54.649
Bruce Willis?

15:54.692 --> 15:56.259
No, the weather.

15:56.303 --> 15:58.870
-Marge, it's going to rain
during the show.
-How hard?

15:58.914 --> 16:02.918
Well, let's just say I hope youliked the movie Waterworld.

16:02.962 --> 16:05.616
Ambitious, eh, but unsatisfying.

16:05.660 --> 16:07.618
You might want
to consider canceling.

16:07.662 --> 16:10.621
I don't know much about showbiz,but I know one thing:

16:10.665 --> 16:12.797
the show must go on.

16:12.841 --> 16:14.625
Huh? I never heard that before.

16:14.669 --> 16:16.845
Really? Well, tell me
to break a leg.

16:16.888 --> 16:19.456
Why would I do that?
It's violent and cruel.

16:19.500 --> 16:22.068
Well-- there's no business
like show business.

16:22.111 --> 16:23.634
Nah, nah, now that's not true.

16:23.678 --> 16:25.071
Most show business companies

16:25.114 --> 16:27.247
are part of much larger
conglomerates.

16:27.290 --> 16:29.162
Just get the hell out.

16:29.205 --> 16:31.033
ThatI've heard before.

16:32.295 --> 16:33.035
[grunts]

16:33.079 --> 16:34.254
Hmm.

16:34.297 --> 16:36.430
Going live.
Break a leg, everyone.

16:36.473 --> 16:38.432
-MAN: What?
-MAN 2:
Why would you wish that?

16:38.475 --> 16:40.129
LENNY:
You're mean.

16:40.173 --> 16:43.045
[piano playing]

16:43.089 --> 16:45.221
♪ Let me tell you
about a mystery ♪

16:45.265 --> 16:46.657
♪ Of our city's history ♪

16:46.701 --> 16:48.485
♪ An out-of-towner
was our founder ♪

16:48.529 --> 16:50.270
♪ Despite his latent bigotry ♪

16:50.313 --> 16:52.489
♪ How did this pioneer
domineer ♪

16:52.533 --> 16:55.318
♪ Persevere,
then die right here? ♪

16:55.362 --> 16:58.495
♪ Before the tire fire,
a man named Jebediah ♪

16:58.539 --> 17:02.021
-♪ Made Springfield
the new frontier... ♪
-[mouthing]

17:03.500 --> 17:05.154
Cue camera three.

17:05.198 --> 17:06.503
Cue Bart.

17:08.027 --> 17:09.506
Whoa.

17:09.550 --> 17:13.336
[deep voice]: ♪ That's right, my
name is Jebediah Springfield ♪

17:13.380 --> 17:16.339
♪ There is none
to whom I yield ♪

17:16.383 --> 17:18.124
♪ No king to whom I've kneeled ♪

17:18.167 --> 17:22.998
♪ Tonight
my secrets are revealed ♪

17:25.044 --> 17:31.267
♪ Jebediah Springfield ♪

17:35.315 --> 17:37.273
[hip-hop beat playing]

17:37.317 --> 17:40.711
♪ Now, this bear and I
are one and the same ♪

17:40.755 --> 17:43.584
♪ He gave his life
so that I could have fame ♪

17:43.627 --> 17:46.587
♪ Jebediah Springfield. ♪

17:46.630 --> 17:48.154
MARGE:
Cut to commercial.

17:48.197 --> 17:51.766
That's a cut
to commercial, everyone.

17:51.809 --> 17:53.376
John Lithgow?

17:53.420 --> 17:55.248
I like to work.

17:55.291 --> 17:57.467
-Oh, uh, line, please?
-"Grrr."

17:57.511 --> 18:00.209
No, you fool, a rescue line.

18:00.253 --> 18:01.776
Mom, what do we do?

18:01.819 --> 18:03.386
Improvise.

18:03.430 --> 18:06.172
Lisa, I need a five-minute rap
about the cruelty of the sea

18:06.215 --> 18:08.783
and the brave souls
who rise above it.

18:08.826 --> 18:11.829
No problem. Can I make sly
analogies to today's politics?

18:11.873 --> 18:13.048
No. You'll date it.

18:15.659 --> 18:17.574
♪ The bullets flew like rain ♪

18:17.618 --> 18:19.054
♪ As buffalo were slain... ♪

18:19.098 --> 18:21.796
Who wants to change the channel?

18:21.839 --> 18:23.624
Eh, either they're all dead
or it's a hit.

18:23.667 --> 18:25.191
Fifty-fifty.

18:25.234 --> 18:27.584
[gasps]

18:27.628 --> 18:31.501
♪ And now I have
a raging fever ♪

18:31.545 --> 18:35.201
♪ Bitten by a rabid beaver ♪

18:35.244 --> 18:38.160
♪ I didn't fight
for equal rights ♪

18:38.204 --> 18:42.817
♪ I wish I'd done more
for non-whites ♪

18:42.860 --> 18:47.169
♪ But no more time
for Jebediah ♪

18:47.213 --> 18:52.174
♪ All that's left to do ♪

18:52.218 --> 18:55.612
♪ Is ♪

18:55.656 --> 18:58.224
♪ Die-a. ♪

18:58.267 --> 19:00.269
[groans in regular voice]

19:03.229 --> 19:05.187
[cheering]

19:05.231 --> 19:06.971
BARNEY:
In unison...

19:07.015 --> 19:08.843
AUDIENCE [chanting]:
Marge! Marge! Marge!

19:08.886 --> 19:11.759
This is the happiest moment...
[choking]

19:11.802 --> 19:14.805
Careers are getting shorter
than ever these days.

19:16.416 --> 19:19.810
Marge, we got the highest ratingin modern TV history.

19:19.854 --> 19:21.595
A 0.6!

19:21.638 --> 19:23.466
Congratulations.

19:23.510 --> 19:27.992
I did it. I directeda popular off-Broadway musical.

19:28.036 --> 19:30.821
And I wrote a popular
off-Broadway musical.

19:30.865 --> 19:33.520
And I caught an octopus
on Main Street. What a day.

19:38.264 --> 19:39.482
And the winnerfor Outstanding Lead Performance

19:39.526 --> 19:41.005
in a Play or Musical.

19:41.049 --> 19:44.095
Oh, mein Gott!It's Sideshow Mel
for The Tempest.

19:44.139 --> 19:46.359
[Krusty the Clown Show
theme song playing]

19:46.402 --> 19:50.450
Barbara, you can put
the kids to bed now.

19:50.493 --> 19:53.714
Is what I'd like to say,
but I'm childless.

19:53.757 --> 19:57.500
"One pie to the groin
won't do damage," they said.

19:57.544 --> 19:59.154
They were wrong!

19:59.198 --> 20:01.461
12 nominations, zero awards.

20:01.504 --> 20:03.811
Welcome to Club Snub, Marge.

20:03.854 --> 20:06.814
Feel the bile rising, the
bitterness that will never...

20:06.857 --> 20:10.948
PRESENTER:
And a special award for
Best Newcomer, Marge Simpson.

20:10.992 --> 20:12.733
-[gasps]
-Damn it!

20:19.218 --> 20:22.264
♪ Ah, hell, give me ♪

20:22.308 --> 20:25.398
♪ A white wine spritzer ♪

20:25.441 --> 20:27.313
♪ Ah, hell, give me ♪

20:27.356 --> 20:31.360
♪ A white wine spritzer ♪

20:52.338 --> 20:55.341
♪ You ♪

20:55.384 --> 20:57.995
♪ Only ♪

20:58.039 --> 20:59.475
♪ Live... ♪

20:59.519 --> 21:01.347
-FRINK [deep voice]:
♪ The end. ♪
-Shh!
